# reorG Prisma / Database Conventions

## Schema Design

- Every table has a `id` field (cuid or uuid)
- Use `@unique` on natural keys (e.g., `sku` on MasterRow, `key` on AppSetting)
- Use explicit foreign key relations with `@relation` — no implicit relations
- Use `DateTime` with `@default(now())` for `createdAt` and `@updatedAt` for `updatedAt`
- Store JSON blobs in `Json` type fields (e.g., `rawData`, `config`, `details`)
- Use enums for fixed sets: `Role`, `Platform`, `SyncStatus`, `ChangeStatus`, `PushStatus`

## Key Tables and Their Purpose

- `MasterRow` — one per unique master-store SKU; holds shared internal data (weight, supplier cost, etc.)
- `MarketplaceListing` — one per marketplace item/variant; linked to MasterRow by SKU; holds live marketplace data
- `StagedChange` — separate from MarketplaceListing; holds user edits until pushed or cancelled
- `Integration` — one per connected store; holds platform type, config, write lock state
- `ShippingRate` — weight-to-cost mapping table
- `SyncJob` / `PushJob` — audit records for sync and push operations
- `AuditLog` — general audit trail
- `Backup` — backup metadata with R2 storage keys

## Migration Safety

- Always review generated SQL before applying migrations
- Never use `prisma db push` in production — use `prisma migrate deploy`
- Name migrations descriptively: `add_staged_change_table`, `add_platform_fee_to_master_row`
- Test migrations against a copy of production data shape before deploying

## Query Patterns

- Use Prisma Client in service functions only (`src/lib/services/`)
- Use `select` or `include` to limit fetched fields — never fetch entire rows with all relations by default
- Use transactions (`prisma.$transaction`) for multi-table writes
- Use `findFirst` with `where` for single-record lookups, not `findMany()[0]`
